  "prompt": "How was the International Space Station built?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a monumental achievement in international cooperation and space exploration. Its construction involved multiple nations, decades of planning, and numerous space missions. Here\u2019s an overview of how it was built:\n\n### 1. **Planning and Collaboration**\n   - The ISS program began in the 1980s as a joint effort among NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), ESA (European Space Agency), JAXA (Japan), and CSA (Canada).\n   - The framework for collaboration was formalized in 1998, with agreements on contributions, responsibilities, and shared use of the station.\n\n### 2. **Assembly in Orbit**\n   - The ISS was constructed in space, piece by piece, over the course of more than a decade. Modules and components were launched into orbit and assembled by astronauts during spacewalks.\n   - The first module, **Zarya (Functional Cargo Block)**, was launched by Russia in November 1998. It provided propulsion, power, and storage for the early stages of the ISS.\n   - Two weeks later, NASA launched **Unity (Node 1)**, the first U.S. module, which connected to Zarya via the Space Shuttle mission STS-88.\n\n### 3. **Expansion and Habitation**\n   - Over the years, additional modules and components were added, including:\n     - **Zvezda (Service Module)** (2000): Provided life support and living quarters.\n     - **Destiny Laboratory Module** (2001): The primary U.S. research facility.\n     - **Columbus Module** (2008): ESA\u2019s primary laboratory.\n     - **Kibo Module** (2008): JAXA\u2019s laboratory.\n   - Solar arrays were deployed to provide power, and trusses were added to support them.\n\n### 4. **Construction Milestones**\n   - The first crew, **Expedition 1**, arrived in November 2000, marking the beginning of continuous human habitation.\n   - Space Shuttles and Russian Soyuz and Progress spacecraft delivered modules, supplies, and crews.\n   - Astronauts and cosmonauts conducted over 40 assembly flights and more than 160 spacewalks to build and maintain the ISS.\n\n### 5. **Completion and Operation**\n   - The ISS was largely completed by 2011, with the final components, including the **Leonardo Permanent Multipurpose Module** and the **Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer**, added during the Space Shuttle\u2019s final missions.\n   - The station is now roughly the size of a football field, with a mass of over 400 tons and a habitable volume equivalent to a six-bedroom house.\n\n### 6. **Ongoing Use and Maintenance**\n   - The ISS serves as a microgravity laboratory for scientific research, technological development, and international collaboration.\n   - It is regularly resupplied and upgraded by cargo spacecraft and crewed missions.\n\nThe ISS stands as a testament to what humanity can achieve through global partnership, innovation, and determination.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
